#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:3
msgid "FAQ"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:8
msgid "Why not just wrap at 80 columns?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:10
msgid ""
"Column wrapping causes paragraph-wide reflows when you change a single "
"word. Reviewers see the entire paragraph in the diff, obscuring the "
"actual edit. Sentence-per-line formatting means a one-word change "
"produces a one-line diff."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:15
msgid "Does this affect how the document renders?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:17
msgid ""
"No. LaTeX, Org-mode, Markdown, and most prose formats treat single "
"newlines as whitespace. Two consecutive newlines start a new paragraph. "
"Snapper preserves paragraph breaks (blank lines) and only changes where "
"single newlines occur within a paragraph."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:22
msgid "My collaborators don't use snapper."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:24
msgid "Will this cause problems?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:26
msgid ""
"No. The formatting affects only whitespace within paragraphs. "
"Collaborators can edit normally and their changes will merge cleanly. For"
" fully transparent integration, use a git smudge/clean filter (see the "
"how-to guide)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:31
msgid "Why does snapper split \"Dr."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:33
msgid "Smith\" correctly?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:35
msgid ""
"Snapper maintains a curated list of 80+ abbreviations (titles, Latin "
"terms, academic references, single-letter initials). After Unicode "
"sentence boundary detection, it merges any splits that occurred at known "
"abbreviation periods. You can add project-specific abbreviations via "
"``.snapperrc.toml``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:40
msgid "What about non-English text?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:42
msgid ""
"The Unicode UAX #29 sentence boundary algorithm works across languages. "
"The abbreviation list currently covers English. A ``--lang`` flag and "
"multi-language abbreviation sets are planned. For languages where rule-"
"based splitting performs poorly, a neural mode (``--neural``, via "
"nnsplit) is planned behind a feature flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:48
msgid "Can I use snapper as a library?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:50
msgid ""
"Yes. The crate (``snapper-fmt``) exposes ``format_text()`` and all "
"internal modules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:67
msgid "How fast is it?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:69
msgid ""
"Snapper processes typical academic papers (10-50 pages) in under 10ms. No"
" runtime dependencies, no network calls, no model loading. The neural "
"mode (when implemented) adds startup cost for model loading."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:74
msgid "What about CRLF line endings?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:76
msgid ""
"Snapper detects the input's line ending convention (LF or CRLF) and "
"preserves it in the output. Internally, processing normalizes to LF and "
"converts back before writing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:80
msgid "How do I report a bug or request a feature?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/faq/index.rst:82
msgid ""
"File an issue at `github.com/TurtleTech-ehf/snapper/issues "
"<https://github.com/TurtleTech-ehf/snapper/issues>`_."
msgstr ""

